By large, environmental policies and transitions can impose potential socio-economic impacts on employment and consumers. Although a healthier environment is likely to have positive effects on employees and consumers, such effects may be minor in some cases, all threatening equality:

                           •

Costs for both producers and consumers are likely to be reduced (e.g. more durable products reduce costs for replacement; lower costs for environmental clean-up and public health generally reduce companies' and consumers' tax burden), but some of the savings will not be equally available to all because of needed higher investments and inter-dependencies associated with equality;


                           •

Sustainable industries create new jobs, but such opportunities are not the same for all people and regions;


                           •

Working conditions (wages, job security, occupational safety, labour rights, etc.) for those who take employment in new sectors may not necessarily improve;


                           •

Some workers may lose their jobs permanently, which also reduces tax revenues and increases public spending, lowers quality of life, and increases social inequalities;


                           •

Carbon taxes and price rise for high-carbon products and services may disproportionately affect lower-income households or other vulnerable groups (e.g. migrants who depend on family travel) [84].
